1
00:00:25,144 --> 00:00:32,630
Hello, everyone, and welcome to Medford Happenings, a show for and about the city of Medford.

2
00:00:33,390 --> 00:00:35,012
And I am John Petrella.

3
00:00:36,193 --> 00:00:51,725
And the purpose of this program is to give Medford citizens facts and information to help you make informed choices and to discover city services or businesses you may not have been aware of.

4
00:00:55,289 --> 00:01:01,436
And our guest today is a very special guest, attorney Nick Gileo.

5
00:01:02,497 --> 00:01:12,087
And Nick has been following the Method High School Project, the City Zoning Initiative, and the Neighborhood Ambassador Program.

6
00:01:12,788 --> 00:01:17,353
And he will give us an update on that a little later on in the show.

7
00:01:18,466 --> 00:01:19,687
A lot to go over, Nick.

8
00:01:19,848 --> 00:01:20,929
Welcome to the show.

9
00:01:21,630 --> 00:01:22,851
Thanks for having me back on, John.

10
00:01:23,272 --> 00:01:24,133
It's our pleasure.

11
00:01:24,173 --> 00:01:25,294
Thank you for joining us.

12
00:01:25,334 --> 00:01:26,355
We appreciate it.

13
00:01:27,437 --> 00:01:34,625
So why don't we begin, Nick, again, give us an introduction to our listeners about who Nick Gileo is.

14
00:01:35,406 --> 00:01:35,686
Sure.

15
00:01:35,887 --> 00:01:38,509
So just to be very brief, my name is Nick Giurleo.

16
00:01:39,029 --> 00:01:41,291
I'm a lifelong resident of West Medford.

17
00:01:42,032 --> 00:01:44,453
In the last election, I ran for city council.

18
00:01:44,974 --> 00:01:47,156
I did not win, but it was a great experience.

19
00:01:47,176 --> 00:01:52,720
I got to meet a lot of wonderful residents and really get a good understanding of what's going on politically in Medford.

20
00:01:53,941 --> 00:01:55,142
As John mentioned, I'm an attorney.

21
00:01:55,162 --> 00:01:57,144
I work for a firm in downtown Boston.

22
00:01:57,825 --> 00:02:07,506
And I've been following very closely various things that have been happening in the city politically, including the zoning, the high school, as well as I was recently appointed to be a neighborhood ambassador.

23
00:02:08,680 --> 00:02:09,780
That's a great thing, yeah.

24
00:02:10,121 --> 00:02:12,281
We're going to talk about that later, Nick.

25
00:02:12,541 --> 00:02:13,802
We're going to get you on that.

26
00:02:14,862 --> 00:02:22,965
So, I know you're really involved with the, you know, the building process.

27
00:02:23,005 --> 00:02:30,068
So, with the high schools, can you tell us where we are in the building process?

28
00:02:32,689 --> 00:02:36,390
Give us a summary, Nick, if you can, of designs being considered.

29
00:02:37,431 --> 00:02:38,111
As of now.

30
00:02:38,552 --> 00:02:39,412
Sure, my pleasure.

31
00:02:39,813 --> 00:02:41,254
So I'll just begin with a disclaimer.

32
00:02:41,574 --> 00:02:45,317
I'm not on the building committee and I'm not many different things.

33
00:02:45,357 --> 00:02:54,124
I'm not an engineer, I'm not an economist, I'm not an educator, but I have been following closely what's been going on just as a citizen who's very interested in this.

34
00:02:54,905 --> 00:02:56,406
where it could potentially take our city.

35
00:02:57,266 --> 00:03:02,448
I am an attorney, so perhaps I have some legal expertise that could be of value.

36
00:03:02,488 --> 00:03:07,990
I've been following the project, and I'm happy to just give an explanation here of where we're at.

37
00:03:08,110 --> 00:03:12,131
The project is currently in the feasibility phase.

38
00:03:12,732 --> 00:03:21,015
The project team, the building committee, is considering different designs for what type of new high school we're going to have.

39
00:03:22,055 --> 00:03:28,141
So, the committee originally had a much larger number of designs, but then decided to narrow it down to six.

40
00:03:28,622 --> 00:03:32,185
So, I'll talk about each of those six designs.

41
00:03:32,485 --> 00:03:44,316
The information I'm getting is from various public documents that are out there, different slides that have been presented, as well as just what various members of the committee have said, as well as other elected leadership.

42
00:03:45,017 --> 00:03:47,438
So, happy to go through each of those designs with you today.

43
00:03:47,458 --> 00:03:48,218
Sounds great.

44
00:03:48,458 --> 00:03:49,659
Yep, sounds good.

45
00:03:50,319 --> 00:03:52,620
And I just want to say one thing before you get into it.

46
00:03:53,040 --> 00:03:55,421
You said some disclaimers at the beginning.

47
00:03:56,001 --> 00:04:01,924
I understand all that, but I just want to let people know that you are very qualified.

48
00:04:02,864 --> 00:04:04,224
You're doing a great job.

49
00:04:05,885 --> 00:04:12,330
You're putting a lot of information out there various ways.

50
00:04:12,770 --> 00:04:13,971
We see it all the time.

51
00:04:14,451 --> 00:04:15,992
You're getting a lot of comments.

52
00:04:17,013 --> 00:04:19,435
And I just think it's a great thing what you're doing, really.

53
00:04:19,595 --> 00:04:21,016
And I thank you for that.

54
00:04:21,596 --> 00:04:22,817
And now you can continue.

55
00:04:22,857 --> 00:04:23,758
Thank you so much, John.

56
00:04:23,798 --> 00:04:26,260
Yeah, I'm glad to hear that positive feedback.

57
00:04:27,788 --> 00:04:29,909
So, like I mentioned, there are six designs.

58
00:04:30,749 --> 00:04:31,630
I'll go through each of them.

59
00:04:32,430 --> 00:04:35,131
Our very first design is a code upgrade.

60
00:04:35,231 --> 00:04:36,792
It's option A.1.

61
00:04:37,452 --> 00:04:42,674
And you can see on your screen here a basic layout of the current high school.

62
00:04:43,294 --> 00:04:47,476
Under this design, there wouldn't be any physical changes to the building.

63
00:04:47,536 --> 00:04:53,298
This would just be to bring the building up to code to essentially repair the existing high school.

64
00:04:54,303 --> 00:04:57,425
Part of that would be to meet what have been called accessibility requirements.

65
00:04:58,525 --> 00:05:02,287
But there would be some kind of ancillary renovations with this that have been mentioned.

66
00:05:03,508 --> 00:05:07,630
Renovations to the parking, to the fields, as well as the pool.

67
00:05:08,850 --> 00:05:12,272
Of all our six designs, this one is the least expensive.

68
00:05:13,572 --> 00:05:15,093
The last estimate we received was $437 million.

69
00:05:17,860 --> 00:05:21,342
And we received some information just about how long it would take.

70
00:05:21,462 --> 00:05:24,283
So it would be estimated to take about 54 months.

71
00:05:25,223 --> 00:05:27,024
How many modular units would be required?

72
00:05:28,105 --> 00:05:30,826
56 units of modular units would be required.

73
00:05:31,646 --> 00:05:34,387
And there was also an assessment done as to whether or not this would

74
00:05:35,888 --> 00:05:47,536
support or hinder a document called the educational plan, which was developed earlier in the process, to determine what are the educational goals for the new high school that we're seeking to build here.

75
00:05:48,396 --> 00:05:57,182
Under the code upgrade, it was determined that that would not be consistent with the educational plan as developed as was ultimately approved by the school committee.

76
00:05:59,053 --> 00:06:01,435
So that's our code upgrade option in a nutshell.

77
00:06:01,815 --> 00:06:04,937
I'll move on to the next one, which is option B1.2.

78
00:06:05,217 --> 00:06:09,460
This is the first of our addition renovation options.

79
00:06:10,241 --> 00:06:15,885
And as you can see from this diagram, this would be a two-story addition to the central part of the high school.

80
00:06:16,565 --> 00:06:19,787
It would be about 150,000 new square feet.

81
00:06:21,188 --> 00:06:24,430
Regarding the fields and pools, there'd be light renovation to both of those.

82
00:06:25,190 --> 00:06:27,191
But parking, we'd see a significant difference.

83
00:06:27,311 --> 00:06:33,655
We'd see a two-and-a-half-story underground parking garage with just a small amount of parking above grade.

84
00:06:34,655 --> 00:06:39,558
It was discussed that there could be alternatives to this garage, such as taking away a field.

85
00:06:40,439 --> 00:06:42,680
That would allow us to place all the parking above grade.

86
00:06:44,055 --> 00:06:48,517
This second to the code upgrade is the next least expensive option.

87
00:06:48,958 --> 00:06:51,699
The last estimate we received was $825 million.

88
00:06:52,740 --> 00:06:55,761
And it would take about the same length as doing a code upgrade.

89
00:06:55,781 --> 00:06:56,922
It would take 54 months.

90
00:06:57,702 --> 00:07:00,524
And it would require just a little bit less modular units.

91
00:07:00,784 --> 00:07:01,684
The estimate for that was 46.

92
00:07:03,104 --> 00:07:08,447
Can I just, modular units, can you explain exactly what that is?

93
00:07:08,827 --> 00:07:11,928
So my understanding of a modular unit is similar to a trailer.

94
00:07:12,369 --> 00:07:18,832
It would be an outside structure to temporarily place students while the construction was ongoing.

95
00:07:19,412 --> 00:07:27,016
So obviously if you're building inside a building, you know, there are places the students can't be, so you need to put them somewhere else to keep the continuity of learning.

96
00:07:27,236 --> 00:07:28,997
So that's obviously part of the cost of

97
00:07:30,471 --> 00:07:33,155
Yes, I believe that is factored into the cost.

98
00:07:33,315 --> 00:07:44,631
I remember hearing at one of the meetings that the MSBA, which is the state authority that grants us money to fund the project, would not cover the cost of those modular units.

99
00:07:47,647 --> 00:07:51,630
So that takes us to the next option, which would be C2.2.

100
00:07:51,750 --> 00:07:57,574
This is an addition renovation option, so the second addition renovation option.

101
00:07:58,574 --> 00:08:09,982
And you can see from this diagram that the central premise of the project here would be to demolish most of the existing building and replace it with what looks like a scissor-shaped structure.

102
00:08:10,002 --> 00:08:12,284
You can see it on the left side of that diagram.

103
00:08:12,984 --> 00:08:14,125
It would be about 500,000 new square feet.

104
00:08:17,748 --> 00:08:22,893
Regarding parking, we learned that this one would have a one-story underground parking garage.

105
00:08:22,913 --> 00:08:25,236
There would be a little bit of parking above grade.

106
00:08:27,110 --> 00:08:34,812
And like with the other option that I discussed, the other addition renovation, you could reduce that size of the field.

107
00:08:35,172 --> 00:08:36,892
So with the other project, it was get rid of a field.

108
00:08:36,912 --> 00:08:42,493
This would be just take away a portion of the field and you could put some of the parking above grade, so above ground.

109
00:08:43,833 --> 00:08:48,674
This one is estimated at 833 million, the last estimate that we received.

110
00:08:49,775 --> 00:08:51,415
And it would take about 51 months.

111
00:08:52,655 --> 00:08:56,556
It's important to note that the project designs were recently changed at a Monday meeting

112
00:08:57,107 --> 00:08:58,207
of the school building committee.

113
00:08:59,108 --> 00:09:04,309
And some of the changes that were made were looking at ways to get rid of the modular classroom units.

114
00:09:04,909 --> 00:09:09,030
So this design originally had modular classroom units required.

115
00:09:09,210 --> 00:09:13,832
That was modified to allow no mods required.

116
00:09:13,992 --> 00:09:18,813
So currently C2.2 would not require any sort of modular classrooms.

117
00:09:19,687 --> 00:09:26,391
which many residents who have spoken at these building committee meetings have expressed their displeasure for modular learning.

118
00:09:26,411 --> 00:09:28,992
They don't want their students learning what would essentially be trailers.

119
00:09:29,353 --> 00:09:32,634
They don't want their students to be in a normal kind of classroom environment.

120
00:09:32,734 --> 00:09:37,257
So I think that's something very positive that we're seeing is trying to get rid of the need for these mods.

121
00:09:37,277 --> 00:09:39,858
It doesn't seem like a good environment.

122
00:09:40,339 --> 00:09:41,319
Yeah, I would agree.

123
00:09:41,339 --> 00:09:44,781
I can't imagine you'd be learning very well in what's effectively a trailer.

124
00:09:44,841 --> 00:09:45,341
Yeah, no.

125
00:09:47,442 --> 00:09:52,807
So that takes us to the next addition renovation option, which would be C3.4.

126
00:09:53,969 --> 00:10:02,657
This option is to demolish most of the existing building and replace it with a triangular shaped new structure.

127
00:10:03,538 --> 00:10:08,603
That structure, and you can see it right now on the diagram, that structure would be about 600,000 new square feet.

128
00:10:11,810 --> 00:10:17,833
Regarding the parking, that would have us with a one-story underground parking garage.

129
00:10:18,713 --> 00:10:20,534
Again, there would be a small amount of surface parking.

130
00:10:20,614 --> 00:10:31,840
Again, we learned at the last meeting, there's been this discussion going, well, we could tamper with the size of fields and reduce the size of the field and put some of the parking above ground.

131
00:10:32,760 --> 00:10:37,844
And, you know, there's different reasons why I think a person might prefer a parking garage to above-ground parking.

132
00:10:38,765 --> 00:10:44,270
I think aesthetically, I mean, in a lot of ways, it's nice not to have an above-ground parking garage.

133
00:10:44,990 --> 00:10:51,996
But at the same time, I think there can be safety concerns with parking garages as well.

134
00:10:52,236 --> 00:10:52,677
Underground, yeah.

135
00:10:54,458 --> 00:10:55,718
you know, would worry about.

136
00:10:57,159 --> 00:10:58,919
And, you know, you're always looking at cost, too.

137
00:10:58,959 --> 00:11:05,000
Maybe it would, I would imagine it would take more to build an underground parking garage than an above ground one or above ground parking.

138
00:11:05,380 --> 00:11:06,681
I would guess so, yeah, Nick.

139
00:11:06,841 --> 00:11:09,081
You know, it would involve some blasting, I would suspect.

140
00:11:09,141 --> 00:11:09,481
Oh, yeah.

141
00:11:10,161 --> 00:11:10,801
I would guess so.

142
00:11:10,821 --> 00:11:12,262
A lot more digging, too.

143
00:11:12,582 --> 00:11:14,322
So, just a few more things about this design.

144
00:11:15,022 --> 00:11:18,863
So, Edgar Lee Field and two of the practice fields, they would be renovated.

145
00:11:19,887 --> 00:11:26,028
And this design was also, it was mentioned at the Monday meeting, this was the first I heard of this, was they would potentially construct a new stadium.

146
00:11:26,068 --> 00:11:30,189
You can see at one end of the diagram, and that's where it would go.

147
00:11:30,209 --> 00:11:34,310
So it'd be a new stadium with the multi-purpose fields and not just for one sport.

148
00:11:36,090 --> 00:11:40,871
And this project, we have a cost at about 833 million.

149
00:11:41,732 --> 00:11:48,133
And like that previous renovation addition, about 51 months to do this.

150
00:11:48,939 --> 00:11:51,380
So they're all in the same time frame.

151
00:11:51,920 --> 00:11:56,521
I'm just curious, what about the field we have now up there?

152
00:11:56,541 --> 00:11:57,761
What about the field of dreams?

153
00:11:58,502 --> 00:12:01,622
Yeah, so it looks like with that design, that would be kept.

154
00:12:01,863 --> 00:12:02,743
It is going to be kept.

155
00:12:03,103 --> 00:12:05,524
But it looks like they want to add more field space.

156
00:12:05,544 --> 00:12:09,165
All of these designs, I think, are more or less contemplating adding more field space.

157
00:12:09,865 --> 00:12:16,266
And with that design, the last thing to say is they were able to modify it, so there would be no modular classroom units needed.

158
00:12:16,286 --> 00:12:16,907
Oh, that's nice.

159
00:12:17,307 --> 00:12:17,667
OK.

160
00:12:17,827 --> 00:12:17,987
Yep.

161
00:12:19,911 --> 00:12:26,475
So that takes us through the addition renovation options, and now we move on to the new construction.

162
00:12:26,495 --> 00:12:30,797
There are two new construction options under consideration.

163
00:12:30,817 --> 00:12:35,980
It's important to say that the MSBA requires a code upgrade option, which we have.

164
00:12:37,762 --> 00:12:45,926
But from there, you know, it's very much to the discretion of the committee as to the number of renovation addition and new construction options that they want.

165
00:12:46,427 --> 00:12:49,408
So we have now two new construction considerations.

166
00:12:49,428 --> 00:12:49,708
Okay.

167
00:12:49,728 --> 00:12:56,252
The committee, by the way, is aware of what the MSBA will pay and what they won't pay.

168
00:12:56,292 --> 00:12:58,994
There are certain things I, from what I understand,

169
00:13:00,097 --> 00:13:02,579
I don't have a lot of knowledge, but I do have some.

170
00:13:02,779 --> 00:13:09,004
The math is pretty complicated, but it's all spelled out how they calculate that reimbursement rate in the MSBA regulations.

171
00:13:09,685 --> 00:13:12,748
So there's state laws that talk about how they make that calculations.

172
00:13:12,808 --> 00:13:18,292
The committee is nowhere near making that, getting that calculated number yet.

173
00:13:18,352 --> 00:13:19,893
But eventually we will have that number.

174
00:13:20,834 --> 00:13:24,717
So just talking about D1.1 here, our new construction option,

175
00:13:25,798 --> 00:13:33,040
So this new structure would be about 600,000 square feet, 600,000 square feet of a new building.

176
00:13:33,060 --> 00:13:37,721
And you can see it's placed where the main parking lot is today.

177
00:13:37,741 --> 00:13:43,002
So you come up to the high school from Winthrop Street, where you pull in to park, that would be where the new school is.

178
00:13:43,522 --> 00:13:49,003
And we would build a new field where the existing high school is.

179
00:13:49,624 --> 00:13:55,205
And we'd be keeping, but with some renovations, Edgerly Field and the practice fields.

180
00:13:56,346 --> 00:14:03,590
So this one would also have an underground parking garage and some small amount of surface parking.

181
00:14:04,311 --> 00:14:09,534
One of the things a lot of people were talking about, residents were concerned about the pool, you know, what's going to happen to the pool?

182
00:14:10,135 --> 00:14:11,876
It's such a valuable community resource.

183
00:14:12,336 --> 00:14:12,737
Correct.

184
00:14:13,497 --> 00:14:14,378
It certainly is.

185
00:14:15,078 --> 00:14:18,521
With this design, the proposal is not to renovate the pool.

186
00:14:18,681 --> 00:14:20,502
The other designs talked about renovating the pool.

187
00:14:20,542 --> 00:14:24,445
This is to build a new pool, and it would be a standalone structure.

188
00:14:24,465 --> 00:14:26,967
It would be separate from the main building.

189
00:14:27,427 --> 00:14:33,152
You can see that little orangish box in the corner there, that's where the pool would be.

190
00:14:33,172 --> 00:14:35,593
You can see it's not connected directly to the building.

191
00:14:37,143 --> 00:14:40,105
So this option here, unfortunately, this one's the most expensive.

192
00:14:40,365 --> 00:14:40,765
Of course.

193
00:14:40,905 --> 00:14:42,166
That's been estimated so far.

194
00:14:42,186 --> 00:14:43,866
We're at $893 million.

195
00:14:44,147 --> 00:14:45,307
Right.

196
00:14:45,747 --> 00:14:51,130
And that would make it one of the most expensive projects in probably state history.

197
00:14:51,150 --> 00:14:53,351
Yeah, that's an extremely high number.

198
00:14:53,391 --> 00:14:55,712
I mean, let's be honest, that's a lot of money.

199
00:14:55,772 --> 00:14:56,833
It is quite a bit of money.

200
00:14:57,833 --> 00:15:01,335
Of course, there's a lot of things to think about, such as, you know, where we're at in the process right now.

201
00:15:01,375 --> 00:15:01,575
Yes.

202
00:15:01,995 --> 00:15:05,237
And how much the MSBA will ultimately reimburse, as well as.

203
00:15:05,557 --> 00:15:05,737
Right.

204
00:15:06,237 --> 00:15:07,057
space reductions.

205
00:15:07,578 --> 00:15:17,201
This Monday meeting, there was talk about reducing some of the space to try to bring the cost down, and the committee did vote on some cuts for that.

206
00:15:19,102 --> 00:15:26,164
This project, again, they were able to modify it so the modular learning classrooms would not be required, so that's another benefit.

207
00:15:26,245 --> 00:15:27,465
I think that's a big benefit.

208
00:15:29,063 --> 00:15:33,866
And then finally here we have D2.1, new construction.

209
00:15:34,786 --> 00:15:36,507
This is the second new construction option.

210
00:15:36,527 --> 00:15:43,431
You can see it's kind of flipped from where that other new construction design placed the school.

211
00:15:44,032 --> 00:15:48,595
The other design placed it coming up from Winthrop Street, pulling into the school where the main parking lot is.

212
00:15:48,895 --> 00:15:52,437
This design would build the new high school essentially where Edgar Lee Field is currently.

213
00:15:52,457 --> 00:15:52,917
In the back.

214
00:15:53,337 --> 00:15:53,698
In the back.

215
00:15:54,638 --> 00:15:55,098
Exactly.

216
00:15:55,319 --> 00:15:57,981
And again, this would be over 600,000 square feet.

217
00:15:59,822 --> 00:16:02,865
This one would have garage space underground.

218
00:16:03,485 --> 00:16:10,230
Again, considering do we want to take away some of that field space and put some of the parking above ground.

219
00:16:11,371 --> 00:16:13,531
And you can also see there'd be a standalone pool as well.

220
00:16:14,292 --> 00:16:21,013
The diagram shows that again, that orange box structure that's kind of separated from the rest of it.

221
00:16:21,033 --> 00:16:23,113
That's more or less where the pool would be.

222
00:16:24,233 --> 00:16:26,354
So that's a proposal with this as well.

223
00:16:27,594 --> 00:16:31,194
This project is a little cheaper than the other new construction.

