00:20:56,507 --> 00:20:59,270
So there's kind of two aspects to the Medford Square zoning.

276
00:20:59,430 --> 00:21:07,858
I'll start with the first aspect here, which is what was created on Tuesday night by vote of the City Council, and that is a new Medford Square zoning district.

277
00:21:08,959 --> 00:21:15,545
So I'll give you just a few highlights of what this zoning amendment contains.

278
00:21:16,005 --> 00:21:17,527
So you can see the map on your screen here.

279
00:21:17,987 --> 00:21:19,689
That is the new district mapped out.

280
00:21:20,269 --> 00:21:30,236
The black dotted line encompasses the borders of the district and you'll see divisions into different colors within that odd shape.

281
00:21:30,836 --> 00:21:32,117
Those are called sub-districts.

282
00:21:32,398 --> 00:21:34,739
So there's the district and then there's the sub-districts.

283
00:21:35,179 --> 00:21:48,308
And the sub-districts have different requirements as to things like uses and dimensional requirements as well as other aspects of the zoning law that was passed.

284
00:21:49,289 --> 00:21:52,251
So this process was done fairly quickly.

285
00:21:52,652 --> 00:22:00,037
January 2 now is a pretty short period of time to draft a law that's gonna have such a tremendous impact on the way our square looks.

286
00:22:01,678 --> 00:22:06,862
But there were several meetings and the Community Development Board was very invested in trying to get this right.

287
00:22:07,402 --> 00:22:10,364
And I think they did their due diligence very, very well.

288
00:22:10,865 --> 00:22:15,868
So you'll see with the four sub-districts, they allow between four to eight stories as of right.

289
00:22:17,249 --> 00:22:20,812
and that additional incentive based stories can be added as well.

290
00:22:20,852 --> 00:22:28,959
There's different incentives such as affordability that can be utilized by the developers to get these extra floors essentially to build higher.

291
00:22:30,040 --> 00:22:32,522
In terms of density, you'll see that the highest density is

292
00:22:33,425 --> 00:22:49,035
the uh part kind of close to where city hall is the senior center right those city-owned lots yep and part of that has to do with helping the developer transom build its project i'll talk a little bit about the details of that in a bit but um the higher density areas will be

293
00:22:49,582 --> 00:22:51,043
in that part of the square.

294
00:22:51,843 --> 00:22:57,686
Would it be possible, Nick, just for the people watching at home and looking at the chart, could you call out the colors?

295
00:22:58,206 --> 00:23:02,668
Sure, so you'll see there's a key to the left-hand side.

296
00:23:02,688 --> 00:23:07,070
That actually will help you coordinate which sub-district is which.

297
00:23:07,090 --> 00:23:08,590
Awesome, I'm sorry, I didn't even see that.

298
00:23:08,610 --> 00:23:15,793
So I would refer people to that if you're trying to understand where the particular number of stories is allowed in which sub-district.

299
00:23:17,234 --> 00:23:24,499
So, the stated purpose of this zoning is to promote more housing, more density in the square, more mixed-use structures.

300
00:23:25,179 --> 00:23:29,322
The zoning ordinance contains uses that allow for mixed-use.

301
00:23:29,442 --> 00:23:38,948
I believe the previous zoning did not even mention mixed-use structures, so there was really an intent here to implement mixed-use structures into the zoning ordinance.

302
00:23:39,568 --> 00:23:40,769
law that was created here.

303
00:23:41,389 --> 00:23:49,315
Walkability was another stated purpose as well, let's make a square a little more walkable, a little more easier to navigate on your feet.

304
00:23:50,476 --> 00:24:01,685
In the table of uses, so the uses are what is allowed in the square, we see various changes that I think reflect aesthetic desires for the square, reflect what we want our square to look like.

305
00:24:02,845 --> 00:24:04,266
One that was discussed was banks.

306
00:24:04,867 --> 00:24:07,409
Some have argued that there are way too many banks in Medford Square.

307
00:24:07,429 --> 00:24:08,850
I actually totally agree with that.

308
00:24:09,130 --> 00:24:10,751
There are a lot of banks, yeah.

309
00:24:11,532 --> 00:24:12,713
Nothing on the banking industry.

310
00:24:12,793 --> 00:24:14,594
No, nothing against them, I hear you.

311
00:24:14,634 --> 00:24:17,697
But yeah, there's quite a lot of banks in Medford Square.

312
00:24:18,157 --> 00:24:20,819
We could maybe have different types of businesses in their spots.

313
00:24:20,859 --> 00:24:23,001
I think of what happened to Salvatore's, which is very sad.

314
00:24:23,101 --> 00:24:26,624
Yeah, I think everyone was hoping for a restaurant over there.

315
00:24:27,044 --> 00:24:30,389
So under the new zoning, you need a special permit to get a bank.

316
00:24:30,569 --> 00:24:31,911
It's not allowed outright.

317
00:24:31,931 --> 00:24:37,679
You have to go to the Community Development Board and they have to give you a special permit if you want to open a bank.

318
00:24:39,101 --> 00:24:42,886
Another use that was added was neighborhood medical offices.

319
00:24:43,887 --> 00:24:52,951
So if you remember with the Salem Street zoning, there was a big controversy over whether or not the zoning allowed for a methadone clinic on Salem Street.

320
00:24:53,631 --> 00:24:59,054
And this all had to do with this term, neighborhood medical office, which was a use defined for that zoning district.

321
00:24:59,854 --> 00:25:07,677
So there was a lot of back and forth with that, but ultimately with this zoning district, it's allowed as of right.

322
00:25:07,697 --> 00:25:13,480
I think a lot of people might have missed that, that you can build a neighborhood medical office as of right under the new Medford Square zoning.

323
00:25:14,963 --> 00:25:20,747
Whether or not that would lead to a developer coming in and possibly wanting to open a methadone clinic, I mean, that remains to be seen.

324
00:25:21,328 --> 00:25:25,351
I mean, there's probably practical and political reasons that might motivate them not to do that.

325
00:25:25,771 --> 00:25:30,074
But ultimately, if you look at just legally, yes, they could do it under this new zoning.

326
00:25:30,234 --> 00:25:34,958
And there really wasn't any discussion or debate on whether or not that was a good thing.

327
00:25:35,038 --> 00:25:37,800
I recommended a special permit required for it.

328
00:25:37,820 --> 00:25:39,461
So in other words, discretionary.

329
00:25:39,881 --> 00:25:42,823
Give the Community Development Board discretion whether or not to grant that type of permit.

330
00:25:44,165 --> 00:25:46,087
And then just some other things I'll quickly run through.

331
00:25:46,788 --> 00:25:53,235
Neighborhood cafes is a use that was mentioned, maker spaces, breweries and tap rooms.

332
00:25:54,337 --> 00:25:57,240
Another that was interesting is no funeral homes in the new district.

333
00:25:57,741 --> 00:25:58,642
Can't build a funeral home.

334
00:25:58,662 --> 00:26:00,384
Can't put a funeral home.

335
00:26:00,584 --> 00:26:01,705
Not even with a special permit.

336
00:26:01,885 --> 00:26:02,106
Wow.

337
00:26:02,902 --> 00:26:03,082
Yeah.

338
00:26:03,422 --> 00:26:06,364
And there wasn't really any discussion about that either, what the motive for that was.

339
00:26:06,844 --> 00:26:11,726
And I think part of this has to do with, you know, in the end of the day, practically, who writes our zoning?

340
00:26:11,867 --> 00:26:15,648
It's really the consultant and the planning office of our city.

341
00:26:16,169 --> 00:26:16,549
Okay.

342
00:26:16,589 --> 00:26:18,110
Director Alicia Hunt's office.

343
00:26:19,410 --> 00:26:24,173
In a lot of ways, I think the city councilors are very, like, disconnected from, like, what exactly is happening.

344
00:26:24,713 --> 00:26:31,478
with the zoning and they're relying quite a bit on others to tell them, you know, this is the type of zoning we want or desire.

345
00:26:32,438 --> 00:26:37,762
And I think we have to be wary about that because ultimately we need leaders who are lawmakers.

346
00:26:37,982 --> 00:26:39,583
You think about it, what is a lawmaker?

347
00:26:40,003 --> 00:26:40,984
A person who makes laws.

348
00:26:41,184 --> 00:26:41,825
Absolutely.

349
00:26:42,065 --> 00:26:44,406
If you don't know how to make a law, should you be a lawmaker?

350
00:26:44,426 --> 00:26:46,448
In my opinion, no.

351
00:26:46,588 --> 00:26:47,889
No, absolutely no.

352
00:26:48,069 --> 00:26:48,329
Yeah.

353
00:26:49,290 --> 00:26:52,612
So that's just kind of some highlights of that and I'll move on to

354
00:26:53,730 --> 00:26:58,092
the transom project, because I know that's another aspect of this that I think bears mentioning.

355
00:26:58,112 --> 00:27:09,456
I just want to mention, you brought up a lot of things that I don't think, I'm going to say a large part of the population in Method is not aware of.

356
00:27:10,239 --> 00:27:16,644
Yeah, you know, one of my kind of things that I really harp on a lot is it's important to get into the details.

357
00:27:17,124 --> 00:27:22,868
There's some people who are satisfied with these kind of surface level analyses of things, like for example affordable housing.

358
00:27:22,888 --> 00:27:30,394
There are people who say we need more affordable housing and there'll be people who say, you know, will argue the contrary essentially.

359
00:27:31,134 --> 00:27:34,458
And then we kind of have these surface-level discussions back and forth on that.

360
00:27:34,718 --> 00:27:44,810
But let's get into details and talk about why specific proposals cause certain changes, and whether or not our decision-making, just as a pragmatic matter, makes sense.

361
00:27:45,571 --> 00:27:46,672
And that's really been my focus.

362
00:27:46,732 --> 00:27:49,816
I like to go into the details and try to understand what exactly is happening.

363
00:27:51,477 --> 00:27:52,778
I think that's important.

364
